Her husband followed and purchased her freedom shortly afterward. The Meachums ran a school for free and enslaved black people in the First African Baptist Church  which they later moved to a floating steamboat on the Mississippi River when the state of Missouri banned education for blacks in 1847. After the death of her husband in 1854  Meachum continued running their home on Fourth Street as a ‚Äòsafe house‚Äô on the Underground Railroad. On May 21  1855  after an attempt to ferry nine enslaved people across the Mississippi River to freedom in Illinois  Meachum and a freedman named Isaac were arrested for breaking the Fugitive Slave Law of 1850.
